{
  "An open system exchanges:": "",
  "Neither matter nor energy with its surroundings": "",
  "Only matter, not energy": "",
  "Both matter and energy with its surroundings": "",
  "Only energy, not matter": "",
  "An open system exchanges both matter and energy with its surroundings. Most natural ecosystems are open systems because they receive solar energy and exchange gases, water, and nutrients.": "",
  "A closed system exchanges:": "",
  "Energy but not matter with its surroundings": "",
  "Both matter and energy": "",
  "Neither matter nor energy": "",
  "A closed system exchanges energy but not matter with its surroundings. Earth is approximately a closed system because it receives solar energy and radiates heat but exchanges very little matter with space.": "",
  "Negative feedback loops in environmental systems tend to:": "",
  "Counteract changes and maintain stability (homeostasis) in the system": "",
  "Amplify changes and destabilize the system": "",
  "Always cause extinction": "",
  "Have no effect on the system": "",
  "Negative feedback loops counteract or reverse a change in a system, helping to maintain equilibrium. For example, increased predator populations reduce prey, which then reduces predators, stabilizing both.": "",
  "Positive feedback loops in environmental systems tend to:": "",
  "Amplify the initial change, pushing the system further from equilibrium": "",
  "Stabilize the system": "",
  "Always produce beneficial outcomes": "",
  "Positive feedback loops amplify an initial change, moving the system further from its original state. For example, melting ice exposes dark water that absorbs more heat, accelerating further melting.": "",
  "The ice-albedo feedback is an example of a:": "",
  "Positive feedback loop where melting ice reduces reflectivity, increasing warming, which melts more ice": "",
  "Closed system that does not interact with climate": "",
  "Negative feedback loop that cools the Earth": "",
  "Static system with no feedback": "",
  "The ice-albedo feedback is a positive feedback loop: warming melts reflective ice, exposing darker ocean or land that absorbs more solar radiation, causing further warming and more melting.": "",
  "Earth is best described as a(n) _____ system with respect to matter.": "",
  "Open, freely exchanging both matter and energy with surrounding interstellar space environments": "",
  "Constantly gaining significant amounts of matter from space through meteorite impacts and cosmic dust": "",
  "Approximately closed (receives energy from the sun but exchanges very little matter with space)": "",
  "Completely isolated, exchanging neither matter nor energy with its surrounding space environment": "",
  "Earth is approximately closed with respect to matter, meaning the same atoms are recycled through biogeochemical cycles. It is open with respect to energy, receiving sunlight and radiating heat.": "",
  "A system at dynamic equilibrium is:": "",
  "Growing continuously without any limits or constraints on its expansion and resource consumption": "",
  "Maintaining a relatively stable state while processes continue at equal rates in both directions": "",
  "Completely still with absolutely no activity, processes, or movement occurring within the system": "",
  "Steadily declining toward inevitable collapse and complete loss of all functional organization": "",
  "Dynamic equilibrium means a system appears stable overall even though internal processes are continuously occurring. For example, a lake at equilibrium has water entering and leaving at roughly equal rates.": "",
  "Inputs to an ecosystem include:": "",
  "Only predators that migrate into the ecosystem from adjacent habitats and surrounding territories": "",
  "Only waste products generated by metabolic processes within the organisms of the existing ecosystem": "",
  "Solar energy, water, nutrients, and organisms that enter the system": "",
  "Only heat loss through radiation and convection from the ecosystem surface to the atmosphere above": "",
  "System inputs are the energy, matter, and information that flow into a system from outside. For ecosystems, these include solar energy, precipitation, nutrient inflows, and immigrating organisms.": "",
  "A tipping point in an environmental system occurs when:": "",
  "The system is perfectly balanced and all processes have reached a permanent stable equilibrium state": "",
  "Nothing changes in the system and all environmental variables remain completely constant over time": "",
  "A small change pushes the system past a critical threshold, causing rapid, often irreversible shifts to a new state": "",
  "The system returns to normal quickly and automatically after experiencing a relatively small change": "",
  "A tipping point is a critical threshold beyond which a small additional change triggers a large, often irreversible shift in the system's state, such as coral reef collapse or ice sheet disintegration.": "",
  "Body temperature regulation in humans is an example of a:": "",
  "An open system with no internal regulation or control mechanisms governing temperature changes": "",
  "A tipping point where the body shifts irreversibly to an entirely new physiological temperature range": "",
  "A positive feedback loop that amplifies temperature changes and pushes the body toward extremes": "",
  "Negative feedback loop that maintains homeostasis around 37 degrees C": "",
  "Human thermoregulation is a classic negative feedback loop: when body temperature rises, sweating cools the body; when it falls, shivering generates heat, maintaining a stable internal temperature.": "",
  "What is a feedback loop?": "",
  "An audio sound system that creates echoing reverberations by reflecting acoustic waves off surfaces": "",
  "A one-way linear path of energy transfer that never returns to or influences the starting point": "",
  "A recreational roller coaster design featuring circular loops and repeated acceleration patterns": "",
  "A circular pathway in which the output of a system influences the input, either amplifying or dampening the original change": "",
  "A feedback loop is a mechanism where the output of a process cycles back to affect the input, creating either a self-reinforcing (positive) or self-correcting (negative) cycle within the system.": "",
  "What is homeostasis?": "",
  "A type of house designed for stable temperatures": "",
  "A medical condition affecting the bones": "",
  "The tendency of systems to rapidly change": "",
  "The tendency of a system to maintain relatively stable internal conditions through self-regulating feedback mechanisms": "",
  "Homeostasis is the ability of a system to maintain internal stability through negative feedback mechanisms that counteract disturbances, keeping conditions within a viable range for the system to function.": "",
  "What is a tipping point in environmental science?": "",
  "The moment when a species first appears in an ecosystem": "",
  "The highest point of a mountain": "",
  "A restaurant gratuity added to an environmental bill": "",
  "The point at which a gradual change triggers a rapid, often irreversible shift in a system to a fundamentally different state": "",
  "An environmental tipping point is a critical threshold where a relatively small change causes a disproportionately large and often irreversible shift in system behavior, like the collapse of a fishery.": "",
  "What is resilience in the context of environmental systems?": "",
  "The ability of a system to absorb disturbances and recover to its original state without fundamentally changing": "",
  "The speed at which organisms reproduce": "",
  "The tendency of a system to collapse permanently": "",
  "A type of building material": "",
  "Resilience is the capacity of an ecosystem or environmental system to withstand disturbances (like fires, floods, or pollution) and return to its previous functional state rather than shifting to a new one.": "",
  "What is albedo?": "",
  "The fraction of incoming solar radiation reflected by a surface back into space": "",
  "The temperature of the ocean surface": "",
  "A measure of wind speed": "",
  "A type of cloud formation": "",
  "Albedo measures the reflectivity of a surface, expressed as a fraction from 0 (absorbs all light) to 1 (reflects all light). Snow and ice have high albedo, while dark surfaces like asphalt have low albedo.": "",
  "What is an emergent property?": "",
  "A property that is always present in individual components": "",
  "A characteristic of a system that arises from the interactions of its components and cannot be predicted from the parts alone": "",
  "A property of an emergency response team": "",
  "A newly discovered chemical element": "",
  "Emergent properties arise from interactions between system components and cannot be predicted by studying parts in isolation. For example, the ability of a forest to regulate climate emerges from the collective action of trees, soil, and water.": "",
  "What is a system in environmental science?": "",
  "A government regulation or policy directive mandating specific environmental protection procedures": "",
  "Only a computer network consisting of interconnected hardware and software processing components": "",
  "A single isolated organism that exists independently without any connections to other living things": "",
  "A set of interacting components that form a complex whole, with inputs, outputs, and internal processes": "",
  "In environmental science, a system is a set of interconnected components that work together as a unified whole, with defined boundaries, inputs (energy, matter), internal processes, and outputs.": "",
  "What is a steady state?": "",
  "A condition in which inputs to a system equal outputs, so the system's overall condition remains constant over time": "",
  "A system that is completely static with no processes occurring": "",
  "A US state with no environmental changes": "",
  "A permanently frozen lake": "",
  "A steady state occurs when system inputs balance outputs, maintaining overall stability even though processes continue within the system. It does not mean the system is static or unchanging internally.": "",
  "What does 'threshold' mean in systems thinking?": "",
  "A critical level or value beyond which a system undergoes a significant change in behavior or state": "",
  "The maximum height that a tree species can achieve under ideal growing conditions in its habitat": "",
  "A geological type of rock formation created by metamorphic or sedimentary processes underground": "",
  "The physical entrance to a building or structure, particularly the doorway or point of entry": "",
  "A threshold is a critical boundary in a system beyond which a qualitative change occurs. Crossing an environmental threshold can trigger rapid, dramatic shifts that may be difficult or impossible to reverse.": "",
  "What is systems thinking?": "",
  "Studying each component of a system in complete isolation": "",
  "An approach that examines how components of a system interrelate and affect one another within the context of the whole": "",
  "A type of systematic exercise routine": "",
  "Thinking only about computer systems": "",
  "Systems thinking is an analytical approach that considers how individual components interact within a larger system, recognizing that the behavior of the whole emerges from these interconnections.": "",
  "As Arctic temperatures rise, permafrost (permanently frozen soil) begins to thaw, releasing methane — a potent greenhouse gas. This methane causes more warming, which thaws more permafrost, releasing even more methane. This scenario is an example of:": "",
  "A positive feedback loop where warming accelerates further warming through methane release": "",
  "A closed system with no external effects": "",
  "Dynamic equilibrium": "",
  "A negative feedback loop that stabilizes the climate": "",
  "The permafrost-methane feedback is a positive feedback loop: warming thaws permafrost, releasing methane that causes more warming, which thaws more permafrost. This self-amplifying cycle accelerates climate change.": "",
  "A lake ecosystem has been absorbing moderate nutrient pollution for years without visible effects. However, after one particularly heavy fertilizer runoff event, the lake suddenly shifts to an algae-dominated state with frequent fish kills that persist even after pollution is reduced. This illustrates:": "",
  "Normal seasonal variation": "",
  "A tipping point where the system crossed a threshold and shifted to a new, difficult-to-reverse state": "",
  "A steady state that was never disrupted": "",
  "A negative feedback loop restoring the lake": "",
  "This lake crossed a tipping point. The system absorbed stress for years (resilience), but once the threshold was exceeded, it shifted rapidly to a eutrophic state that resists reversal even after the stressor is reduced.": "",
  "Predator-prey relationships often show oscillating population cycles: when prey increases, predators increase, which reduces prey, which then reduces predators, allowing prey to increase again. This cycling pattern is maintained by:": "",
  "Positive feedback that amplifies both populations indefinitely": "",
  "External forces that set population numbers": "",
  "No feedback mechanism at all": "",
  "Negative feedback loops that regulate both populations around a dynamic equilibrium": "",
  "Predator-prey oscillations are maintained by negative feedback: increasing prey fuels predator growth, which reduces prey, which then reduces predators, creating a self-regulating cycle around equilibrium.": "",
  "A forest is cleared for agriculture. Without tree roots holding soil, erosion increases, making it harder for trees to regrow. Without trees, more soil erodes, making regrowth even harder. This degradation cycle is an example of:": "",
  "Normal forest succession where disturbed land naturally regenerates through predictable ecological stages": "",
  "A negative feedback loop where natural processes gradually restore the forest to its original condition": "",
  "A positive feedback loop where deforestation accelerates soil loss, which further prevents forest recovery": "",
  "Dynamic equilibrium being maintained as the system self-corrects and balances opposing environmental forces": "",
  "This is a positive feedback loop of degradation: tree removal causes erosion, which prevents regrowth, causing more erosion. Such cycles can turn forests into barren landscapes without intervention.": "",
  "Scientists studying climate change note that increased CO2 may initially boost plant growth (which absorbs CO2, a negative feedback), but extreme warming can cause droughts and wildfires that kill forests (releasing CO2, a positive feedback). This shows that:": "",
  "Feedback loops never interact with each other": "",
  "Only one type of feedback exists in climate systems": "",
  "Complex environmental systems contain both positive and negative feedback loops that may interact and shift in dominance": "",
  "Climate change will automatically be corrected by plants": "",
  "Real environmental systems contain multiple interacting feedback loops. Whether a system stabilizes or destabilizes depends on the relative strength of competing positive and negative feedbacks.": "",
  "A coral reef has survived minor temperature increases for decades through its resilience. However, a prolonged heat wave bleaches 80% of the coral, and the reef shifts to an algae-dominated ecosystem that does not support the same biodiversity. An AP exam question might ask you to identify this as:": "",
  "A negative feedback restoring the reef": "",
  "A system crossing a tipping point and shifting to a new, lower-functioning regime": "",
  "Normal coral behavior": "",
  "A steady state being maintained": "",
  "This scenario describes a regime shift where the coral reef ecosystem crosses a tipping point and transitions to a fundamentally different state (algae-dominated) that is resistant to reversal.": "",
  "In an AP free-response question, you are asked to explain how the water cycle is an example of a system with inputs, outputs, and feedback. A strong answer would include:": "",
