  "Only naming the three physical phases of water: solid ice, liquid water, and gaseous water vapor": "",
  "Identifying inputs (solar energy, precipitation), outputs (evaporation, runoff), and feedback mechanisms (e.g., more evaporation leads to more clouds, which can increase precipitation or reflect sunlight)": "",
  "Only providing a textbook definition of the water cycle without discussing specific system components": "",
  "AP free-response questions require identifying system components (inputs, outputs, processes) and explaining feedback mechanisms. The water cycle contains both positive and negative feedbacks involving clouds and temperature.": "",
  "A city builds more roads to reduce traffic congestion. However, the new roads attract more drivers (induced demand), creating even worse congestion, leading to demands for yet more roads. This urban planning problem is an example of:": "",
  "A system at perfect equilibrium": "",
  "A negative feedback loop solving the problem": "",
  "A positive feedback loop where the attempted solution amplifies the original problem": "",
  "A closed system with no inputs": "",
  "Induced demand is a positive feedback loop in transportation systems: building more roads encourages more driving, which increases congestion, prompting more road-building. Systems thinking reveals why this approach fails.": "",
  "An island ecosystem has maintained stable populations of plants, herbivores, and predators for centuries. When humans introduce a non-native predator, the native herbivores are quickly eliminated because they have no defenses. Plants overgrow without herbivores, and the native predator starves. This demonstrates:": "",
  "That ecosystems are immune to disruption": "",
  "That island ecosystems have no food webs": "",
  "That introduced species always improve ecosystems": "",
  "How disrupting one component of a system can cascade through interconnected feedback loops, destabilizing the entire system": "",
  "This demonstrates how interconnected system components depend on feedback loops for stability. Disrupting one link (introducing a new predator) cascades through the system, illustrating why systems thinking is essential.": "",
